# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hallucination-mitigation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Research suggests that fact-checking can indeed correct perceptions among citizens, as well as discourage politicians from spreading false or misleading claims.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] However, corrections may decay over time or be overwhelmed by cues from elites who promote less accurate claims.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Political fact-checking is sometimes criticized as being opinion journalism.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Sensationalist newspapers in the 1850s and later led to a gradual need for a more factual media.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Colin Dickey has described the subsequent evolution of fact-checking.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] More recently, the mainstream media has come under severe economic threat from online startups.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In addition, the rapid spread of misinformation and conspiracy theories via social media is slowly creeping into mainstream media.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] One solution is for more media staff to be assigned a fact-checking role, as for example The Washington Post.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Independent fact-checking organisations have also become prominent, such as PolitiFact.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] External *post hoc* fact-checking organizations first arose in the US in the early 2000s, and the concept grew in relevance and spread to various other countries during the 2010s.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] External *post hoc* fact-checking by independent organizations began in the United States in the early 2000s.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In the 2010s, particularly following the 2016 election of Donald Trump as US President, fact-checking gained a rise in popularity and spread to multiple countries mostly in Europe and Latin America.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] However, the US remains the largest market for fact-checking.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] One 2016 study finds that fact-checkers PolitiFact, FactCheck.org, and *The Washington Post*'s Fact Checker overwhelmingly agree on their evaluations of claims.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A 2018 paper found little overlap in the statements checked by different fact-checking organizations.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] This paper compared 1,178 published fact-checks from PolitiFact with 325 fact-checks from *The Washington Post*'s Fact Checker, and found only 77 statements (about 5%) that both organizations checked.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] For those 77 statements, the fact-checking organizations gave the same ratings for 49 statements and similar ratings for 22, about 92% agreement.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Different fact-checking organizations have shown different tendencies in their choice of which statements they publish fact-checks about.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] For example, some are more likely to fact-check a statement about climate change being real, and others are more likely to fact-check a statement about climate change being fake.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Studies have shown that fact-checking can affect citizens' belief in the accuracy of claims made in political advertisement.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A 2017 study in the *Journal of Politics* found that "individuals consistently update political beliefs in the appropriate direction, even on facts that have clear implications for political party reputations, though they do so cautiously and with some bias...
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A study by Yale University cognitive scientists Gordon Pennycook, Adam Bear, Evan Collins, and David G.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Rand found that Facebook tags of fake articles "did significantly reduce their perceived accuracy relative to a control without tags, but only modestly".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A Dartmouth study led by Brendan Nyhan found that Facebook tags had a greater impact than the Yale study found.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A "disputed" tag on a false headline reduced the number of respondents who considered the headline accurate from 29% to 19%, whereas a "rated false" tag pushed the number down to 16%.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A 2019 study found that the "disputed" tag reduced Facebook users' intentions to share a fake news story.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The Yale study found evidence of a backfire effect among Trump supporters younger than 26 years whereby the presence of both untagged and tagged fake articles made the untagged fake articles appear more accurate.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In response to research which questioned the effectiveness of the Facebook "disputed" tags, Facebook decided to drop the tags in December 2017 and would instead put articles which fact-checked a fake news story next to the fake news story link whenever it is shared on Facebook.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Large studies by Ethan Porter and Thomas J.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Individuals' preexisting beliefs, ideology, and knowledge affected to what extent the fact-checking had an impact.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A 2018 study found that Republicans were more likely to correct their false information on voter fraud if the correction came from Breitbart News rather than a non-partisan neutral source such as PolitiFact.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A 2022 study found that individuals exposed to a fact-check of a false statement by a far-right politician were less likely to share the false statement.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Some studies have found that exposure to fact-checks had durable effects on reducing misperceptions, whereas other studies have found no effects.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Scholars have debated whether fact-checking could lead to a "backfire effect" whereby correcting false information may make partisan individuals cling more strongly to their views.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] One study found evidence of such a "backfire effect", but several other studies did not.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A 2015 experimental study found that fact-checking can encourage politicians to not spread misinformation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The study found that it might help improve political discourse by increasing the reputational costs or risks of spreading misinformation for political elites.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The researchers sent, "a series of letters about the risks to their reputation and electoral security if they were caught making questionable statements.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A study of Trump supporters during the 2016 presidential campaign found that while fact-checks of false claims made by Trump reduced his supporters' belief in the false claims in question, the corrections did not alter their attitudes towards Trump.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A 2019 study found that "summary fact-checking", where the fact-checker summarizes how many false statements a politician has made, has a greater impact on reducing support for a politician than fact-checking of individual statements made by the politician.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Individual readers perform some types of fact-checking, such as comparing claims in one news story against claims in another.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] According to Queen's University Belfast researcher Jennifer Rose, because fake news is created with the intention of misleading readers, online news consumers who attempt to fact-check the articles they read may incorrectly conclude that a fake news article is legitimate.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Rose states, "A diligent online news consumer is likely at a pervasive risk of inferring truth from false premises" and suggests that fact-checking alone is not enough to reduce fake news consumption.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Despite this, Rose asserts that fact-checking "ought to remain on educational agendas to help combat fake news".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The term fake news became popularized with the 2016 United States presidential election, causing concern among some that online media platforms were especially susceptible to disseminating disinformation and misinformation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Fake news articles tend to come from either satirical news websites or from websites with an incentive to propagate false information, either as clickbait or to serve a purpose.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The language, specifically, is typically more inflammatory in fake news than real articles, in part because the purpose is to confuse and generate clicks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Furthermore, modeling techniques such as n-gram encodings and bag of words have served as other linguistic techniques to estimate the legitimacy of a news source.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] On top of that, researchers have determined that visual-based cues also play a factor in categorizing an article, specifically some features can be designed to assess if a picture was legitimate and provides us more clarity on the news.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] There is also many social context features that can play a role, as well as the model of spreading the news.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Websites such as "Snopes" try to detect this information manually, while certain universities are trying to build mathematical models to assist in this work.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Some individuals and organizations publish their fact-checking efforts on the internet.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] These may have a special subject-matter focus, such as Snopes.com's focus on urban legends or the Reporters' Lab at Duke University's focus on providing resources to journalists.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The adaptation of social media as a legitimate and commonly used platform has created extensive concerns for fake news in this domain.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The spread of fake news via social media platforms such as Facebook, Twitter and Instagram presents the opportunity for extremely negative effects on society therefore new fields of research regarding fake news detection on social media is gaining momentum.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] However, fake news detection on social media presents challenges that renders previous data mining and detection techniques inadequate.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] As such, researchers are calling for more work to be done regarding fake news as characterized against psychology and social theories and adapting existing data mining algorithms to apply to social media networks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Further, multiple scientific articles have been published urging the field further to find automatic ways in which fake news can be filtered out of social media timelines.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Lateral reading, or getting a brief overview of a topic from lots of sources instead of digging deeply into one, is a popular method professional fact-checkers use to quickly get a better sense of the truth of a particular claim.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Since the 2016 United States presidential election, fake news has been a popular topic of discussion by President Trump and news outlets.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The reality of fake news had become omnipresent, and a lot of research has gone into understanding, identifying, and combating fake news.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Also, a number of researchers began with the usage of fake news to influence the 2016 presidential campaign.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] One research found evidence of pro-Trump fake news being selectively targeted on conservatives and pro-Trump supporters in 2016.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The researchers found that social media sites, Facebook in particular, to be powerful platforms to spread certain fake news to targeted groups to appeal to their sentiments during the 2016 presidential race.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Additionally, researchers from Stanford, NYU, and NBER found evidence to show how engagement with fake news on Facebook and Twitter was high throughout 2016.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Recently, a lot of work has gone into helping detect and identify fake news through machine learning and artificial intelligence.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In 2018, researchers at MIT's CSAIL created and tested a machine learning algorithm to identify false information by looking for common patterns, words, and symbols that typically appear in fake news.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] More so, they released an open-source data set with a large catalog of historical news sources with their veracity scores to encourage other researchers to explore and develop new methods and technologies for detecting fake news.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In 2022, researchers have also demonstrated the feasibility of falsity scores for popular and official figures by developing such for over 800 contemporary elites on Twitter as well as associated exposure scores.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] There are also demonstrations of platform-built-in (by-design) as well browser-integrated (currently in the form of addons) misinformation mitigation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Efforts such as providing and viewing structured accuracy assessments on posts "are not currently supported by the platforms".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Trust in the default or, in decentralized designs, user-selected providers of assessments (and their reliability) as well as the large quantities of posts and articles are two of the problems such approaches may face.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Moreover, they cannot mitigate misinformation in chats, print-media and TV.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The concept for International Fact-Checking Day was introduced at a conference for journalists and fact-checkers at the London School of Economics and Political Science in June 2014.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The holiday was officially created in 2016 and first celebrated on April 2, 2017.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The idea for International Fact-Checking day rose out of the many misinformation campaigns found on the internet, particularly social media sites.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] It rose in importance after the 2016 elections, which brought fake news, as well as accusations of it, to the forefront of media issues.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The holiday is held on April 2 because "April 1 is a day for fools.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] April 2 is a day for facts." Activities for International Fact-Checking Day consist of various media organizations contributing to fact-checking resources, articles, and lessons for students and the general public to learn more about how to identify fake news and stop the spread of misinformation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] 2020's International Fact-Checking Day focused specifically on how to accurately identify information about COVID-19.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Research has shown that fact-checking has limits, and can even backfire, which is when a correction increases the belief in the misconception.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Critics argue that political fact-checking is increasingly used as opinion journalism.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Criticism has included that fact-checking organizations in themselves are biased or that it is impossible to apply absolute terms such as "true" or "false" to inherently debatable claims.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In September 2016, a Rasmussen Reports national telephone and online survey found that "just 29% of all Likely U.S.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Voters trust media fact-checking of candidates' comments.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] A paper by Andrew Guess (of Princeton University), Brendan Nyhan (Dartmouth College) and Jason Reifler (University of Exeter) found that consumers of fake news tended to have less favorable views of fact-checking, in particular Trump supporters.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Deceptive websites that pose as fact-checkers have also been used to promote disinformation; this tactic has been used by both Russia and Turkey.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Facebook announced it would "remove false or debunked claims about the novel coronavirus which created a global pandemic", based on its fact-checking partners, collectively known as the International Fact-Checking Network.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] This reignited debates into the notion of scientific consensus.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In an article published by the medical journal The BMJ, journalist Laurie Clarke said "The contentious nature of these decisions is partly down to how social media platforms define the slippery concepts of misinformation versus disinformation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] This decision relies on the idea of a scientific consensus.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Several commentators have noted limitations of political post-hoc fact-checking.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] They further argue that political fact-checking focuses exclusively on describing facts over making moral judgments (ex., the is–ought problem), assert that it relies on public reason to attempt to discredit public figures, and question its effectiveness on conspiracy theories or fascism.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Likewise, writing in The Hedgehog Review in 2023, Jonathan D.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Gleason assert that fact-checking is ineffective against propaganda for at least three reasons: "First, since much of what skillful propagandists say will be true on a literal level, the fact-checker will be unable to refute them.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Second, no matter how well-intentioned or convincing, the fact-check will also spread the initial claims further.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] As a potential step to a solution, the authors suggest the need of a "scientific community" to establish falsifiable theories, "which in turn makes sense of the facts", noting the difficulty that this step would face in the digital media landscape of the Internet.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] In 2022 and 2023, many social media platforms such as Meta, YouTube and Twitter have significantly reduced resources in Trust and safety, including fact-checking.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Twitter under Elon Musk has severely limited access by academic researchers to Twitter's API by replacing previously free access with a subscription that starts at $42,000 per month, and by denying requests for access under the Digital Services Act.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Many fact-checkers rely heavily on social media platform partnerships for funding, technology and distributing their fact-checks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The term "fact-check" is also appropriated and overused by "partisan sites", which may lead people to "disregard fact-checking as a meaningless, motivated exercise if all content is claimed to be fact-checked".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Fact-checking journalists have been harassed online and offline, ranging from hate mail and death threats to police intimidation and lawfare.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Operators of some fact-checking websites in China admit to self-censorship.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Fact-checking websites in China often avoid commenting on political, economic, and other current affairs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Several Chinese fact-checking websites have been criticized for lack of transparency with regard to their methodology and sources, and for following Chinese propaganda.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Among the benefits of printing only checked copy is that it averts serious, sometimes costly, problems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] These problems can include lawsuits for mistakes that damage people or businesses, but even small mistakes can cause a loss of reputation for the publication.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The loss of reputation is often the more significant motivating factor for journalists.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Fact-checkers verify that the names, dates, and facts in an article or book are correct.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] For example, they may contact a person who is quoted in a proposed news article and ask the person whether this quotation is correct, or how to spell the person's name.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Fact-checkers are primarily useful in catching accidental mistakes; they are not guaranteed safeguards against those who wish to commit journalistic frauds.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Professional fact-checkers have generally been hired by newspapers, magazines, and book publishers, probably starting in the early 1920s with the creation of *Time* magazine in the United States, though they were not originally called "fact-checkers".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Fact-checkers may be aspiring writers, future editors, or freelancers engaged other projects; others are career professionals.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Historically, the field was considered women's work, and from the time of the first professional American fact-checker through at least the 1970s, the fact-checkers at a media company might be entirely female or primarily so.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] The number of people employed in fact-checking varies by publication.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Some organizations have substantial fact-checking departments.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] For example, *The New Yorker* magazine had 16 fact-checkers in 2003 and the fact-checking department of the German weekly magazine *Der Spiegel* counted 70 staff in 2017.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Others may hire freelancers per piece or may combine fact-checking with other duties.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Magazines are more likely to use fact-checkers than newspapers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Television and radio programs rarely employ dedicated fact-checkers, and instead expect others, including senior staff, to engage in fact-checking in addition to their other duties.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Stephen Glass began his journalism career as a fact-checker.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] He went on to invent fictitious stories, which he submitted as reportage, and which fact-checkers at *The New Republic* (and other weeklies for which he worked) never flagged.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] Michael Kelly, who edited some of Glass's concocted stories, blamed himself, rather than the fact-checkers, saying: "Any fact-checking system is built on trust ...
[src:hallucination-mitigation/fact-checking] If a reporter is willing to fake notes, it defeats the system.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a **hallucination** or **artificial hallucination** (also called **bullshitting**, **confabulation**, or **delusion**) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Since the 1980s, the term "hallucination" has been used in computer vision with a positive connotation to describe the process of adding detail to an image.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For example, the task of generating high-resolution face images from low-resolution inputs is called face hallucination.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The first documented use of the term "hallucination" in this sense is in the PhD thesis of Eric Mjolsness in 1986.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A notable work is the face hallucination algorithm by Simon Baker and Takeo Kanade published in 1999.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In the 2000s, hallucinations were described in statistical machine translation as a failure mode.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Since the 2010s, the term has undergone a semantic shift to signify the generation of factually incorrect or misleading outputs by AI systems in tasks like machine translation and object detection.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2015, hallucinations were identified in visual semantic role labeling tasks by Saurabh Gupta and Jitendra Malik.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2015, computer scientist Andrej Karpathy used the term "hallucinated" in a blog post to describe his recurrent neural network (RNN) language model generating an incorrect citation link.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In July 2021, Meta warned during its release of BlenderBot 2 that the system is prone to "hallucinations", which Meta defined as "confident statements that are not true".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Following OpenAI's ChatGPT release in beta version in November 2022, some users complained that such chatbots often seem to pointlessly embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within their generated content.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Many news outlets, including *The New York Times*, started to use the term "hallucinations" to describe these models' frequently incorrect or inconsistent responses.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, the Cambridge dictionary updated its definition of hallucination to include this new sense specific to the field of AI.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers have highlighted a lack of consistency in how the term is used, but also identified several alternative terms in the literature, such as confabulations, fabrications, and factual errors.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Journalist Benj Edwards, in *Ars Technica*, writes that the term "hallucination" is controversial, but that some form of metaphor remains necessary; Edwards suggests "confabulation" as an analogy for processes that involve "creative gap-filling".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In July 2024, a White House report on fostering public trust in AI research mentioned hallucinations only in the context of reducing them.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Notably, when acknowledging David Baker's Nobel Prize-winning work with AI-generated proteins, the Nobel committee avoided the term entirely, instead referring to "imaginative protein creation".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers also use the derogatory term "botshit", often referring to uncritical use of AI.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In the scientific community, some researchers avoid the term "hallucination", seeing it as potentially misleading.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] It has been criticized by Usama Fayyad, executive director of the Institute for Experimental Artificial Intelligence at Northeastern University, on the grounds that it misleadingly personifies large language models and is vague.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Mary Shaw said, "The current fashion for calling generative AI's errors 'hallucinations' is appalling.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Kristina Šekrst argues that applying psychological vocabulary to LLM outputs obscures the difference between the appearance of mental properties and their genuine presence.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Förster & Skop assert that tech companies use the hallucination metaphor to anthropomorphize models and deflect responsibility for non-factual outputs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some see the AI outputs not as illusory but as prospective—that is, having some chance of being true, similar to early-stage scientific conjectures.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The term has also been criticized for its association with psychedelic drug experiences.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Hallucinations can stem from incomplete, inaccurate or unrepresentative data sets.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The pre-training of generative pretrained transformers (GPT) involves predicting the next word.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] It incentivizes GPT models to "give a guess" about what the next word is, even when they lack information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers take an anthropomorphic perspective and posit that hallucinations arise from a tension between novelty and usefulness.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For instance, Amabile and Pratt define human creativity as the production of novel and useful ideas.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By extension, a focus on novelty in machine creativity can lead to the production of original but inaccurate responses—that is, falsehoods—whereas a focus on usefulness may result in memorized content lacking originality.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By 2022, newspapers such as *The New York Times* expressed concern that, as the adoption of bots based on large language models continued to grow, unwarranted user confidence in bot output could lead to problems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, according to interpretability research by Anthropic on Claude, the LLM appears to have internal circuits that cause it to decline to answer questions unless it knows the answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By default, the circuits are active and the LLM doesn't answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When the LLM has sufficient information, these circuits are inhibited and the LLM answers the question.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The researchers said that hallucinations were found to occur when this inhibition happens incorrectly, such as when Claude recognizes a name but lacks sufficient information about that person, causing it to generate plausible but untrue responses.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On 15 November 2022, researchers from Meta AI published Galactica, designed to "store, combine and reason about scientific knowledge".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Content generated by Galactica came with the warning: "Outputs may be unreliable!
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Language Models are prone to hallucinate text." In one case, when asked to draft a paper on creating avatars, Galactica cited a fictitious paper from a real author who works in the relevant area.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Meta withdrew Galactica on 17 November due to offensiveness and inaccuracy.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] OpenAI's ChatGPT, released in beta version to the public on November 30, 2022, was based on the foundation model GPT-3.5 (a revision of GPT-3).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Professor Ethan Mollick of Wharton called it an "omniscient, eager-to-please intern who sometimes lies to you".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Data scientist Teresa Kubacka has recounted deliberately making up the phrase "cycloidal inverted electromagnon" and testing ChatGPT by asking it about the (nonexistent) phenomenon.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] ChatGPT invented a plausible-sounding answer backed with plausible-looking citations that compelled her to double-check whether she had accidentally typed in the name of a real phenomenon.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Other scholars such as Oren Etzioni have joined Kubacka in assessing that such software can often give "a very impressive-sounding answer that's just dead wrong".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When CNBC asked ChatGPT for the lyrics to "Ballad of Dwight Fry", ChatGPT supplied invented lyrics rather than the actual lyrics.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Asked questions about the Canadian province of New Brunswick, ChatGPT got many answers right but incorrectly classified Toronto-born Samantha Bee as a "person from New Brunswick".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Asked about astrophysical magnetic fields, ChatGPT incorrectly volunteered that "(strong) magnetic fields of black holes are generated by the extremely strong gravitational forces in their vicinity".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Other examples involve baiting ChatGPT with a false premise to see if it embellishes upon the premise.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When asked about "Harold Coward's idea of dynamic canonicity", ChatGPT fabricated that Coward wrote a book titled *Dynamic Canonicity: A Model for Biblical and Theological Interpretation*, arguing that religious principles are actually in a constant state of change.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When pressed, ChatGPT continued to insist that the book was real.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Asked for proof that dinosaurs built a civilization, ChatGPT claimed there were fossil remains of dinosaur tools and stated, "Some species of dinosaurs even developed primitive forms of art, such as engravings on stones".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When prompted that "Scientists have recently discovered churros, the delicious fried-dough pastries ...
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] (are) ideal tools for home surgery", ChatGPT claimed that a "study published in the journal *Science*" found that the dough is pliable enough to form into surgical instruments that can get into hard-to-reach places, and that the flavor has a calming effect on patients.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By 2023, analysts considered frequent hallucination to be a major problem in LLM technology, with a Google executive identifying hallucination reduction as a "fundamental" task for ChatGPT competitor Google Gemini.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 demo for Microsoft's GPT-based Bing AI (now Microsoft Copilot) appeared to contain several hallucinations that went uncaught by the presenter.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In June 2023, Mark Walters, a gun rights activist and radio personality, sued OpenAI in a Georgia state court after ChatGPT mischaracterized a legal complaint in a manner alleged to be defamatory against Walters.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The complaint in question was brought in May 2023 by the Second Amendment Foundation against Washington attorney general Robert W.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Ferguson for allegedly violating their freedom of speech, whereas the ChatGPT-generated summary bore no resemblance and claimed that Walters was accused of embezzlement and fraud while holding a Second Amendment Foundation office post that he never held in real life.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] According to AI legal expert Eugene Volokh, OpenAI is likely not shielded against this claim by Section 230, because OpenAI likely "materially contributed" to the creation of the defamatory content.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, Judge Tracie Cason of Gwinnett County Superior Court ruled in favor of OpenAI, stating that the plaintiff had not shown he was defamed, as Walters failed to show that OpenAI's statements about him were negligent or made with "actual malice".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The Tribunal rejected Air Canada's defense that the chatbot was a "separate legal entity that is responsible for its own actions".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In October 2025, several hallucinations, including non-existent academic sources and a fake quote from a federal court judgement were discovered in an A$440,000 report written by Deloitte and submitted to the Australian government in July.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The company later submitted a revised report with these errors removed, and will issue a partial refund to the government.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These weak signals may result in a false positive result for the presence of a sea urchin although there was none in the input image.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Various researchers cited by *Wired* have classified adversarial hallucinations as a high-dimensional statistical phenomenon, or have attributed hallucinations to insufficient training data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers believe that some "incorrect" AI responses classified by humans as "hallucinations" in the case of object detection may in fact be justified by the training data, or even that an AI may be giving the "correct" answer that the human reviewers are failing to see.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For example, an adversarial image that looks, to a human, like an ordinary image of a dog, may in fact be seen by the AI to contain tiny patterns that (in authentic images) would only appear when viewing a cat.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The AI is detecting real-world visual patterns that humans are insensitive to.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Text-to-image models, such as Stable Diffusion, Midjourney and others, often produce inaccurate or unexpected results.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For instance, Gemini depicted Nazi German soldiers as people of color, causing controversy and leading Google to pause image generation involving people in Gemini.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI is also used in photo sleuthing, occasionally causing problems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Luther (2025) describes instances in which generative AI tools used in photo-sleuthing incorrectly identify individuals or fabricate historical matches when analyzing archival military images.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These image-based hallucinations can lead to the spread of misinformation about historical figures, military records, and genealogical research.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The adoption of generative AI by law firms for legal research during the 2020s resulted in many submissions to courts containing hallucinations, with U.S. judges nationwide sanctioning or reprimanding lawyers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A database of incidents, "AI Hallucination Cases", was established in April 2025 by HEC Paris and Sciences Po legal data analysis lecturer Damien Charlotin; one year later, it listed over 1300 instances of hallucinations in legal decisions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In May 2023, it was discovered that Stephen Schwartz had submitted six fake case precedents generated by ChatGPT in his brief to the Southern District of New York on *Mata v.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Avianca, Inc.*, a personal injury case against the airline Avianca.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Schwartz said that he had never previously used ChatGPT, that he did not recognize the possibility that ChatGPT's output could have been fabricated, and that ChatGPT continued to assert the authenticity of the precedents after their nonexistence was discovered.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Kevin Castel dismissed the *Mata* case and issued a $5,000 fine to Schwartz and another lawyer—who had both continued to stand by the fictitious precedents despite Schwartz's previous claims—for bad faith conduct.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Castel characterized numerous errors and inconsistencies in the opinion summaries, describing one of the cited opinions as "gibberish" and "[bordering] on nonsensical".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, high-profile pro se plaintiff Ashley Gjøvik, who has a Juris Doctor from Santa Clara University School of Law, was admonished in U.S.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] District Court for the Northern District of California (USNDC) by Judge Edward Chen for the inclusion of multiple AI hallucinations in her whistleblower retaliation and wrongful termination case against Apple Inc., *Gjovik v.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Apple Inc.*, warning that future instances would result in Gjøvik being held in contempt of court and her pro se privileges revoked.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The case is foundational in Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 11 regarding professional conduct cited repeatedly by other judges as the operative standard.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] It has also been discussed by the American Bar Association in updating the model professional rules and cited in its opinion regarding the use of generative AI.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In September 2025, USNDC Magistrate Judge Peter Kang sanctioned Webb Law attorney Katherine Cervantes for her submission of July 21 that included an AI hallucination which she stated had been obtained from Westlaw AI, the Thomson Reuters' artificial intelligence tool.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On April 28, 2026, Judge Kang sanctioned and fined Webb Law Group managing partner Lenden Webb for insufficient supervision of Cervantes—a junior lawyer incorporating AI for the first time—therefore allowing the legal submission that included an AI hallucinated citation of July 21, 2025.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] During the session, Chief Justice Nels S.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Peterson noted at least five fictitious citations within the filing, as well as five others that did not support the proposition for which they were cited.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On March 30, 2026, Leslie admitted in an affidavit to not verifying AI-generated "expanded legal research" used to prepare the order, which District Attorney Tasha Mosley corroborated in a written apology to Peterson.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On May 5, the Supreme Court vacated the lower court's ruling and ordered for a new order with legitimate citations to be written.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Leslie was also suspended from practicing before the Supreme Court for six months and was ordered to take additional education for ethics and proper use of artificial intelligence.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In April 2026, Sullivan & Cromwell submitted an apology to the U.S.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York, following Boies Schiller Flexner's discovery of hallucinated legal citations that the opposing legal team had submitted to the court on behalf of client Prince Global Holdings Limited.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] As of June 14, 2026, Canadian courts and tribunals have received at least 167 filings containing AI-hallucinated, fictitious citations, across 51 courts and tribunals.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On June 9, 2026, the Chief Justice of Canada, the Right Honourable Richard Wagner, P.C., stated that AI is present in courtrooms "in ways both promising and problematic".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] There are many noted instances of LLMs citing sources that are either incorrect or do not exist.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 study conducted in the *Cureus Journal of Medical Science* showed that out of 178 total references cited by GPT-3, 69 returned an incorrect or nonexistent digital object identifier (DOI).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] An additional 28 had no known DOI nor could be located in a Google search.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Another instance was documented in 2023 by Jerome Goddard from Mississippi State University.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In an experiment, ChatGPT had provided questionable information about ticks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Unsure about the validity of the response, they inquired about the source that the information had been gathered from.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Upon looking at the source, it was apparent that the DOI and the names of the authors had been hallucinated.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some of the authors were contacted and confirmed that they had no knowledge of the paper's existence whatsoever.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Goddard says that, "in [ChatGPT's] current state of development, physicians and biomedical researchers should NOT ask ChatGPT for sources, references, or citations on a particular topic.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Or, if they do, all such references should be carefully vetted for accuracy." The use of these language models is not ready for fields of academic research and that their use should be handled carefully.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Nina Schick said that the persuasive quality of hallucinated content generated by AI systems poses risks to democratic institutions by enabling the spread of convincing but false narratives.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On top of providing incorrect or missing reference material, ChatGPT also has issues with hallucinating the contents of some reference material.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A study that analyzed a total of 115 references provided by ChatGPT-3.5 documented that 47% of them were fabricated.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Another 46% cited real references but extracted incorrect information from them.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Only the remaining 7% of references were cited correctly and provided accurate information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] ChatGPT has also been observed to "double-down" on a lot of the incorrect information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When asked about a mistake that may have been hallucinated, sometimes ChatGPT will try to correct itself but other times it will claim the response is correct and provide even more misleading information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These hallucinated articles generated by language models also pose an issue because it is difficult to tell whether an article was generated by an AI.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] To show this, a group of researchers at the Northwestern University of Chicago generated 50 abstracts based on existing reports and analyzed their originality.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Plagiarism detectors gave the generated articles an originality score of 100%, meaning that the information presented appears to be completely original.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Other software designed to detect AI generated text was only able to correctly identify these generated articles with an accuracy of 66%.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Research scientists had a similar rate of human error, identifying these abstracts at a rate of 68%.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Given the ability of AI generated language to pass as real scientific research in some cases, AI hallucinations present problems for the application of language models in the academic and scientific fields of research due to their ability to be undetectable when presented to real researchers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The high likelihood of returning non-existent reference material and incorrect information may require limitations to be put in place regarding these language models.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some say that rather than hallucinations, these events are more akin to "fabrications" and "falsifications" and that the use of these language models presents a risk to the integrity of the field as a whole.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some academic professionals who support scholarly research, such as academic librarians, have observed a significant increase in workload related to verifying the accuracy of references.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Zoë Teel said in a 2023 paper that universities may need to resort to implementing their own citation auditing in order to track the problem of fictitious references.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some nonexistent phrases such as "vegetative electron microscopy" have appeared in many research papers as a result of having become embedded in AI training data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] At the University of Washington, David Baker's lab has used AI hallucinations to design millions of proteins that do not occur in nature, leading to roughly 100 patents and the founding of over 20 biotech companies.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] This work contributed to Baker receiving the 2024 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, although the committee avoided using the "hallucinations" language.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] At California Institute of Technology, researchers used hallucinations to design a catheter that reduces bacterial contamination.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The design features sawtooth-like spikes on the inner walls that prevent bacteria from gaining traction, potentially reducing the number of urinary tract infections.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These scientific applications of hallucinations differ fundamentally from chatbot hallucinations, as they are grounded in physical reality and scientific facts rather than ambiguous language or internet data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Anima Anandkumar, a professor at Caltech, emphasizes that these AI models are "taught physics" and their outputs must be validated through rigorous testing.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In meteorology, scientists use AI to generate thousands of subtle forecast variations, helping identify unexpected factors that can influence extreme weather events.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] At Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, researchers have applied hallucinatory techniques to enhance blurry medical images, while the University of Texas at Austin has utilized them to improve robot navigation systems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Hallucinations, when constrained by scientific methodology, can significantly accelerate the discovery process.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Artificial intelligence hallucinations can impact education.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] There has been a rise in students using AI tools for assistance in research or writing tools such as Grammarly or using generative AI programs such as ChatGPT.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] This has raised concern regarding academic integrity in submitted projects in addition to hallucinations causing students to learn incorrect information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Part of this concern lies in the citations provided by LLMs and generative AI.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A 2024 study at the University of Mississippi found that many of these citations that students submitted were partially or completely fabricated.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] 47% of these sources either had incorrect titles, dates, authors, or a combination of all.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The study notes that these inconsistencies in student-submitted citations cause educators and librarians to manually check the accuracy more frequently.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The *Journal of Cranio-Maxillofacial Surgery* addresses this risk when it comes to the medical and surgical fields.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] They mention how academic publishers have acknowledged the issue, and that some journals such as *JAMA* have changed some of their policies to discourage the use of AI-generated citations.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Although the journal states that a policy will not be enough to diminish the use of AI-generated citations, automatic tools to check the citations and AI literacy training should also be adopted.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Instructors may use tools such as Turnitin for plagiarism checking and verification of academic integrity.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These tools have been found to sometimes flag papers that have not used any AI assistance in their writing.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] OpenAI has also found such a lack of accuracy in their own AI detection software that the company shut it down entirely.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] As of 2025, there is still ongoing research to try to mitigate the occurrence of hallucinations.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Research in 2022 has shown that language models not only hallucinate but also amplify hallucinations, even for those which were designed to alleviate this issue.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Researchers from OpenAI wrote that hallucinations occur because the training and evaluation of LLMs reward guessing over acknowledging uncertainty, and proposed modifying the scoring of benchmarks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Researchers have proposed a variety of mitigation measures, including getting different chatbots to debate one another until they reach consensus on an answer and neuro-symbolic architectures with formal knowledge bases and inference engines.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Ji et al. divide common mitigation methods into two categories: *data-related methods* and *modeling and inference methods*.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Data-related methods include building a faithful dataset, cleaning data automatically, and information augmentation by augmenting the inputs with external information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Model and inference methods include changes in the architecture (either modifying the encoder, attention, or the decoder in various ways); changes in the training process, such as using reinforcement learning; and post-processing methods that can correct hallucinations in the output.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Nvidia Guardrails, launched in 2023, can be configured to hard-code certain responses via script instead of leaving them to the LLM.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Furthermore, tools such as the Trustworthy Language Model have been created to attempt to aid in the detection of hallucination.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Evaluating multiple possible replies before answering a query by assigning confidence scores to each could mitigate the problem.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] However, this approach would multiply computational costs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Active learning would further increase these costs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In high-stakes domains such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics, the added costs would be operationally necessary in order for LLMs to be used.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In chatbots, however, customers tend to prefer rapid, overconfident answers over cautious, uncertainty-aware ones.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] While it is widely agreed that the output of any NLG process is text, there is some disagreement about whether the inputs of an NLG system need to be non-linguistic.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Common applications of NLG methods include the production of various reports, for example weather and patient reports; image captions; and chatbots like ChatGPT.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Automated NLG can be compared to the process humans use when they turn ideas into writing or speech.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Psycholinguists prefer the term language production for this process, which can also be described in mathematical terms, or modeled in a computer for psychological research.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLG systems can also be compared to translators of artificial computer languages, such as decompilers or transpilers, which also produce human-readable code generated from an intermediate representation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Human languages tend to be considerably more complex and allow for much more ambiguity and variety of expression than programming languages, which makes NLG more challenging.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The practical considerations in building NLU vs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLU needs to deal with ambiguous or erroneous user input, whereas the ideas the system wants to express through NLG are generally known precisely.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLG needs to choose a specific, self-consistent textual representation from many potential representations, whereas NLU generally tries to produce a single, normalized representation of the idea expressed.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLG has existed since ELIZA was developed in the mid 1960s, but the methods were first used commercially in the 1990s.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLG techniques range from simple template-based systems like a mail merge that generates form letters, to systems that have a complex understanding of human grammar.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLG can also be accomplished by training a statistical model using machine learning, typically on a large corpus of human-written texts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The *Pollen Forecast for Scotland* system is a simple example of a simple NLG system that could essentially be based on a template.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] This system takes as input six numbers, which give predicted pollen levels in different parts of Scotland.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] From these numbers, the system generates a short textual summary of pollen levels as its output.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Comparing these two illustrates some of the choices that NLG systems must make; these are further discussed below.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The process to generate text can be as simple as keeping a list of canned text that is copied and pasted, possibly linked with some glue text.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The results may be satisfactory in simple domains such as horoscope machines or generators of personalized business letters.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] However, a sophisticated NLG system needs to include stages of planning and merging of information to enable the generation of text that looks natural and does not become repetitive.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Deciding what information to mention in the text.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] For instance, in the pollen example above, deciding whether to explicitly mention that pollen level is 7 in the southeast.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Overall organisation of the information to convey.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] For example, deciding to describe the areas with high pollen levels first, instead of the areas with low pollen levels.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Merging of similar sentences to improve readability and naturalness.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] should be used when describing a pollen level of 4.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] to refer to a certain region in Scotland.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] An alternative approach to NLG is to use "end-to-end" machine learning to build a system, without having separate stages as above.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] In other words, we build an NLG system by training a machine learning algorithm (often an LSTM) on a large data set of input data and corresponding (human-written) output texts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The end-to-end approach has perhaps been most successful in image captioning, that is automatically generating a textual caption for an image.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] From a commercial perspective, the most successful NLG applications have been *data-to-text* systems which generate textual summaries of databases and data sets; these systems usually perform data analysis as well as text generation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Research has shown that textual summaries can be more effective than graphs and other visuals for decision support, and that computer-generated texts can be superior (from the reader's perspective) to human-written texts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The first commercial data-to-text systems produced weather forecasts from weather data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The earliest such system to be deployed was FoG, which was used by Environment Canada to generate weather forecasts in French and English in the early 1990s.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The success of FoG triggered other work, both research and commercial.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Recent applications include the UK Met Office's text-enhanced forecast.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Data-to-text systems have since been applied in a range of settings.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Following the minor earthquake near Beverly Hills, California on March 17, 2014, The Los Angeles Times reported details about the time, location and strength of the quake within 3 minutes of the event.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] This report was automatically generated by a 'robo-journalist', which converted the incoming data into text via a preset template.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Currently there is considerable commercial interest in using NLG to summarise financial and business data.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Indeed, Gartner has said that NLG will become a standard feature of 90% of modern BI and analytics platforms.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLG is also being used commercially in automated journalism, chatbots, generating product descriptions for e-commerce sites, summarising medical records, and enhancing accessibility (for example by describing graphs and data sets to blind people).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] An example of an interactive use of NLG is the WYSIWYM framework.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] It stands for *What you see is what you meant* and allows users to see and manipulate the continuously rendered view (NLG output) of an underlying formal language document (NLG input), thereby editing the formal language without learning it.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Looking ahead, the current progress in data-to-text generation paves the way for tailoring texts to specific audiences.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] For example, data from babies in neonatal care can be converted into text differently in a clinical setting, with different levels of technical detail and explanatory language, depending on intended recipient of the text (doctor, nurse, patient).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The same idea can be applied in a sports setting, with different reports generated for fans of specific teams.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Over the past few years, there has been an increased interest in automatically generating captions for images, as part of a broader endeavor to investigate the interface between vision and language.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] A case of data-to-text generation, the algorithm of image captioning (or automatic image description) involves taking an image, analyzing its visual content, and generating a textual description (typically a sentence) that verbalizes the most prominent aspects of the image.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] An image captioning system involves two sub-tasks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] In Image Analysis, features and attributes of an image are detected and labelled, before mapping these outputs to linguistic structures.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Recent research utilize*s* deep learning approaches through features from a pre-trained convolutional neural network such as AlexNet, VGG or Caffe, where caption generators use an activation layer from the pre-trained network as their input features.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Text Generation, the second task, is performed using a wide range of techniques.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] For example, in the Midge system, input images are represented as triples consisting of object/stuff detections, action/pose detections and spatial relations.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] These are subsequently mapped to <noun, verb, preposition> triples and realized using a tree substitution grammar.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] A common method in image captioning is to use a vision model (such as a ResNet) to encode an image into a vector, then use a language model (such as an RNN) to decode the vector into a caption.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Despite advancements, challenges and opportunities remain in image capturing research.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Other open challenges include visual question-answering (VQA), as well as the construction and evaluation multilingual repositories for image description.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Another area where NLG has been widely applied is automated dialogue systems, frequently in the form of chatbots.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] A chatbot or chatterbot is a software application used to conduct an on-line chat conversation via text or text-to-speech, in lieu of providing direct contact with a live human agent.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] While natural language processing (NLP) techniques are applied in deciphering human input, NLG informs the output part of the chatbot algorithms in facilitating real-time dialogues.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Early chatbot systems, including Cleverbot created by Rollo Carpenter in 1988 and published in 1997, reply to questions by identifying how a human has responded to the same question in a conversation database using information retrieval (IR) techniques.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Modern chatbot systems predominantly rely on machine learning (ML) models, such as sequence-to-sequence learning and reinforcement learning to generate natural language output.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] For example, the Alibaba shopping assistant first uses an IR approach to retrieve the best candidates from the knowledge base, then uses the ML-driven seq2seq model re-rank the candidate responses and generate the answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Creative language generation by NLG has been hypothesized since the field's origins.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] A recent pioneer in the area is Phillip Parker, who has developed an arsenal of algorithms capable of automatically generating textbooks, crossword puzzles, poems and books on topics ranging from bookbinding to cataracts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] The advent of large pretrained transformer-based language models such as GPT-3 has also enabled breakthroughs, with such models demonstrating recognizable ability for creating-writing tasks.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] A related area of NLG application is computational humor production.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] JAPE (Joke Analysis and Production Engine) is one of the earliest large, automated humor production systems that uses a hand-coded template-based approach to create punning riddles for children.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] HAHAcronym creates humorous reinterpretations of any given acronym, as well as proposing new fitting acronyms given some keywords.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Despite progresses, many challenges remain in producing automated creative and humorous content that rival human output.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] In an experiment for generating satirical headlines, outputs of their best BERT-based model were perceived as funny 9.4% of the time (while real headlines from *The Onion* were 38.4%) and a GPT-2 model fine-tuned on satirical headlines achieved 6.9%.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] It has been pointed out that two main issues with humor-generation systems are the lack of annotated data sets and the lack of formal evaluation methods, which could be applicable to other creative content generation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Some have argued relative to other applications, there has been a lack of attention to creative aspects of language production within NLG.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] NLG researchers stand to benefit from insights into what constitutes creative language production, as well as structural features of narrative that have the potential to improve NLG output even in data-to-text systems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] As in other scientific fields, NLG researchers need to test how well their systems, modules, and algorithms work.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] An ultimate goal is how useful NLG systems are at helping people, which is the first of the above techniques.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] However, task-based evaluations are time-consuming and expensive, and can be difficult to carry out (especially if they require subjects with specialised expertise, such as doctors).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Hence (as in other areas of NLP) task-based evaluations are the exception, not the norm.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Recently researchers are assessing how well human-ratings and metrics correlate with (predict) task-based evaluations.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Work is being conducted in the context of Generation Challenges shared-task events.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] Initial results suggest that human ratings are much better than metrics in this regard.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] In other words, human ratings usually do predict task-effectiveness at least to some degree (although there are exceptions), while ratings produced by metrics often do not predict task-effectiveness well.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] In any case, human ratings are the most popular evaluation technique in NLG; this is contrast to machine translation, where metrics are widely used.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] An AI can be graded on *faithfulness* to its training data or, alternatively, on *factuality*.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] A response that reflects the training data but not reality is faithful but not factual.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] A confident but unfaithful response is a *hallucination*.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/natural-language-generation] In Natural Language Processing, a hallucination is often defined as "generated content that is nonsensical or unfaithful to the provided source content".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG improves LLMs by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Unlike LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG also reduces the need to retrain LLMs with new data, saving on computational and financial costs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Beyond efficiency gains, RAG also allows LLMs to include sources in their responses, so users can verify the cited sources.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] This provides greater transparency, as users can cross-check retrieved content to ensure accuracy and relevance.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] The term retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) was introduced in a 2020 paper that described combining a parametric language model with a non-parametric external memory accessed through retrieval at inference time.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] For example, when Google first demonstrated its LLM tool "Google Bard" (later re-branded to Gemini), the LLM provided incorrect information about the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] This error contributed to a $100 billion decline in Google's stock value.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG is used to prevent these errors, but it does not solve all the problems.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] For example, LLMs can generate misinformation even when pulling from factually correct sources if they misinterpret the context.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] The LLM did not "know" or "understand" the context of the title, generating a false statement.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] LLMs with RAG are programmed to prioritize new information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] This technique has been called "prompt stuffing." Without prompt stuffing, the LLM's input is generated by a user; with prompt stuffing, additional relevant context is added to this input to guide the model's response.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] This approach provides the LLM with key information early in the prompt, encouraging it to prioritize the supplied data over pre-existing training knowledge.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) enhances large language models (LLMs) by incorporating an information-retrieval mechanism that allows models to access and utilize additional data beyond their original training set.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] *Ars Technica* notes that "when new information becomes available, rather than having to retrain the model, all that's needed is to augment the model's external knowledge base with the updated information" ("augmentation").
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] IBM states that "in the generative phase, the LLM draws from the augmented prompt and its internal representation of its training data to synthesize" an answer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Typically, the data to be referenced is converted into LLM embeddings, numerical representations in the form of a large vector space.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG can be used on unstructured (usually text), semi-structured, or structured data (for example knowledge graphs).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] These embeddings are then stored in a vector database to allow for document retrieval.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Given a user query, a document retriever is first called to select the most relevant documents that will be used to augment the query.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] This comparison can be done using a variety of methods, which depend in part on the type of indexing used.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] The model feeds this relevant retrieved information into the LLM via prompt engineering of the user's original query.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Newer implementations (as of 2023) can also incorporate specific augmentation modules with abilities such as expanding queries into multiple domains and using memory and self-improvement to learn from previous retrievals.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Finally, the LLM can generate output based on both the query and the retrieved documents.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Some models incorporate extra steps to improve output, such as the re-ranking of retrieved information, context selection, and fine-tuning.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Retrieval-augmented generation is used in applications where generated responses need to be grounded in external or frequently updated information.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] In healthcare, RAG has been studied as a way to ground large language model outputs in external medical knowledge sources, although reviews have noted continuing challenges around evaluation, ethics, and clinical reliability.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Improvements to the basic process above can be applied at different stages in the RAG flow.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] These methods focus on the encoding of text as either dense or sparse vectors.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Sparse vectors, which encode the identity of a word, are typically dictionary-length and contain mostly zeros.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Dense vectors, which encode meaning, are more compact and contain fewer zeros.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Various enhancements can improve the way similarities are calculated in the vector stores (databases).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Each Retro block consists of Attention, Chunked Cross Attention, and Feed Forward layers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Black-lettered boxes show data being changed, and blue lettering shows the algorithm performing the changes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] By redesigning the language model with the retriever in mind, a 25-time smaller network can get comparable perplexity as its much larger counterparts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Because it is trained from scratch, this method (Retro) incurs the high cost of training runs that the original RAG scheme avoided.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] The hypothesis is that by giving domain knowledge during training, Retro needs less focus on the domain and can devote its smaller weight resources only to language semantics.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] The redesigned language model is shown here.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] It has been reported that Retro is not reproducible, so modifications were made to make it so.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] The more reproducible version is called Retro++ and includes in-context RAG.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Chunking involves various strategies for breaking up the data into vectors so the retriever can find details in it.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Different data styles have patterns that correct chunking can take advantage of.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Sometimes vector database searches can miss key facts needed to answer a user's question.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] One way to mitigate this is to do a traditional text search, add those results to the text chunks linked to the retrieved vectors from the vector search, and feed the combined hybrid text into the language model for generation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG does not prevent hallucinations in LLMs.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] While RAG improves the accuracy of large language models (LLMs), it does not eliminate all challenges.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] One limitation is that while RAG reduces the need for frequent model retraining, it does not remove it entirely.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Additionally, LLMs may struggle to recognize when they lack sufficient information to provide a reliable response.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Without specific training, models may generate answers even when they should indicate uncertainty.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] According to IBM, this issue can arise when the model lacks the ability to assess its own knowledge limitations.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG systems may retrieve factually correct but misleading sources, leading to errors in interpretation.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] In some cases, an LLM may extract statements from a source without considering its context, resulting in an incorrect conclusion.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] Additionally, when faced with conflicting information, RAG models may struggle to determine which source is accurate.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] The worst case outcome of this limitation is that the model may combine details from multiple sources producing responses that merge outdated and updated information in a misleading manner.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/retrieval-augmented-generation] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, these issues occur because RAG systems may misinterpret the data they retrieve.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The **symbol grounding problem** is a concept in the fields of artificial intelligence, cognitive science, philosophy of mind, and semantics.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] It addresses the challenge of connecting symbols, such as words or abstract representations, to the real-world objects or concepts they refer to.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] In essence, it is about how symbols acquire meaning in a way that is tied to the physical world.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] It is concerned with how it is that words (symbols in general) get their meanings, and hence is closely related to the problem of what meaning itself really is.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The problem of meaning is in turn related to the problem of how it is that mental states are meaningful, and hence to the problem of consciousness: what is the connection between certain physical systems and the contents of subjective experiences.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] According to his 1990 paper, Harnad lays out the definition of a "symbol system" relative to his defined symbol grounding problem.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] As Harnad describes that the symbol grounding problem is exemplified in John R.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Searle's Chinese Room argument, the definition of "formal" in relation to formal symbols relative to a formal symbol system may be interpreted from John R.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] A referent is the *thing* that a word or phrase refers to as distinguished from the word's meaning.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] This distinction is closely related to that between the semantic concepts of extension and intension.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Some have interpreted Peirce as addressing the problem of grounding, feelings, and intentionality for the understanding of semiotic processes.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] In recent years, Peirce's theory of signs has been rediscovered by an increasing number of artificial intelligence researchers in the context of symbol grounding problem.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] There would be no connection at all between written symbols and any intended referents if there were no minds mediating those intentions, via their own internal means of picking out those intended referents.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] One's search for meaning would be ungrounded.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] In contrast, the meaning of the words in one's head—those words one *does* understand—are "grounded".
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] That mental grounding of the meanings of words mediates between the words on any external page one reads (and understands) and the external objects to which those words refer.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Another symbol system is natural language.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] On paper or in a computer, language, too, is just a formal symbol system, manipulable by rules based on the arbitrary shapes of words.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] But in the brain, meaningless strings of squiggles become meaningful thoughts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] One property that static paper or, usually, even a dynamic computer lack that the brain possesses is the capacity to pick out symbols' referents.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] This is what we were discussing earlier, and it is what the hitherto undefined term "grounding" refers to.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] A symbol system alone, whether static or dynamic, cannot have this capacity (any more than a book can), because picking out referents is not just a computational (implementation-independent) property; it is a dynamical (implementation-dependent) property.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] To be grounded, the symbol system would have to be augmented with nonsymbolic, sensorimotor capacities—the capacity to interact autonomously with that world of objects, events, actions, properties and states that their symbols are systematically interpretable (by us) as referring to.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] It would have to be able to pick out the referents of its symbols, and its sensorimotor interactions with the world would have to fit coherently with the symbols' interpretations.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The symbols, in other words, need to be connected directly to (i.e., grounded in) their referents; the connection must not be dependent only on the connections made by the brains of external interpreters like us.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Just the symbol system alone, without this capacity for direct grounding, is not a viable candidate for being whatever it is that is really going on in our brains when we think meaningful thoughts.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Meaning as the ability to recognize instances (of objects) or perform actions is specifically treated in the paradigm called "Procedural Semantics", described in a number of papers including "Procedural Semantics" by Philip N.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Johnson-Laird and expanded by William A.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] A brief summary in Woods' paper reads: "The idea of procedural semantics is that the semantics of natural language sentences can be characterized in a formalism whose meanings are defined by abstract procedures that a computer (or a person) can either execute or reason about.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The necessity of groundedness, in other words, takes us from the level of the pen-pal Turing test, which is purely symbolic (computational), to the robotic Turing test, which is hybrid symbolic/sensorimotor.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Meaning is grounded in the robotic capacity to detect, categorize, identify, and act upon the things that words and sentences refer to (see entries for Affordance and for Categorical perception).
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] To categorize is to do the right thing with the right *kind* of thing.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The categorizer must be able to detect the sensorimotor features of the members of the category that reliably distinguish them from the nonmembers.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] These feature-detectors must either be inborn or learned.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The learning can be based on trial and error induction, guided by feedback from the consequences of correct and incorrect categorization; or, in our own linguistic species, the learning can also be based on verbal descriptions or definitions.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The description or definition of a new category, however, can only convey the category and ground its name if the words in the definition are themselves already grounded category names According to Harnad, ultimately grounding has to be sensorimotor, to avoid infinite regress.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Harnad thus points at consciousness as a second property.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] The problem of discovering the causal mechanism for successfully picking out the referent of a category name can in principle be solved by cognitive science.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] But the problem of explaining how consciousness could play an "independent" role in doing so is probably insoluble, except on pain of telekinetic dualism.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] Perhaps symbol grounding (i.e., robotic TT capacity) is enough to ensure that conscious meaning is present, but then again, perhaps not.
[src:hallucination-mitigation/symbol-grounding-problem] In either case, there is no way we can hope to be any the wiser—and that is Turing's methodological point.
